I don=E2=80=99t think AI is going to steal our jobs any time soon, but if y=
ou=E2=80=99re not using tools like ChatGPT to help you work better, you=E2=
=80=99re probably going to have a hard time keeping up with people who are.=
=20
HubSpot's new guide, "How to Use ChatGPT at Work [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/f5877ecd-a77f-44c8-8ca3-6fb341d1bad2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]," cuts through the hype to deliver act=
ionable insights on AI implementation. It covers everything from the basics=
 to very specific prompts you can use, including:=20
Case studies on how high-growth startups are leveraging ChatGPT
Analysis of ChatGPT's impact on various business models
Strategic framework for integrating AI into your workflow
100 prompts used by top-performing teams
Don=E2=80=99t let the robots take your job. Do your job better than the rob=
ots can, with their help.=20
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 112th Weekly Dose of Optimism. Pretty =
varied edition of the Weekly Dose here =E2=80=94 Three Mile Island is back,=
 obesity research, teaching old drugs new tricks, black holes, UFOs , and a=
 history of the U.S. as told through energy. It=E2=80=99s fascinating to me=
 that each week, without fail, there are at least five pieces of inspiring,=
 compelling, and ultimately, optimistic content to share with you. This wee=
k was no different.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
(1) Three Mile Island=E2=80=99s Nuclear Plant to Reopen, Help Power Microso=
ft=E2=80=99s AI Centers [ https://substack.com/redirect/46929da1-764f-4929-=
a0ba-8050247f571d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ]
Jennifer Hiller for The New York Times
Packy here with an emergency last minute addition: Three Mile Island is bac=
k!=20
This morning, The New York Times reported that Constellation Energy Group i=
s reviving the Unit 1 reactor at Three Mile Island and selling the power to=
 Microsoft under a 20-year agreement to power its data centers with clean, =
reliable energy.=20
As Constellation=E2=80=99s CEO Joe Dominguez said, =E2=80=9CThe most import=
ant energy commodity in the world today is a reliable and clean electric me=
gawatt just because of the difficulty of replicating it and the need for it=
=2E=E2=80=9D Amen.=20
This is a real win and a symbolic one. Three Mile Island=E2=80=99s Unit 2 r=
eactor melted down in 1979 in the =E2=80=9Cworst=E2=80=9D nuclear incident =
in the country. =E2=80=9CWorst=E2=80=9D is relative =E2=80=94 no one died, =
no injuries were reported =E2=80=94 but it came just 12 days after the rele=
ase of Jane Fonda=E2=80=99s nuclear-fear-inducing movie, The China Syndrome=
, and effectively put the nail in the coffin of US nuclear growth.=20
Three Mile Island=E2=80=99s Unit 1 reactor actually ran for another 40 year=
s after the meltdown, but shut down in 2019 because it was too costly to ru=
n. US electricity demand was practically flat, and renewables and natural g=
as were able to meet the stagnant need. Over the past couple of years, thou=
gh, demand for electricity has picked up as we start to electrify everythin=
g =E2=80=94 cars, appliances, intelligence, and eventually robots =E2=80=94=
 and reshore manufacturing.=20
When we didn=E2=80=99t need the electricity, we could afford to pretend tha=
t nuclear was unsafe and not as clean as renewables. Now that we do, people=
 are waking up to the fact that nuclear is as clean, safe, and reliable as =
it gets.=20
California kept Diablo Canyon open. Michigan is restarting Palisades. Iowa =
is considering reopening the Duane Arnold Energy Center. And now, Constella=
tion is going to spend $1.6 billion to bring it back and deliver power to M=
icrosoft by 2028.=20
Microsoft will use the power to run data centers to train and run AI models=
, and is looking at using AI to streamline the NRC=E2=80=99s burdensome reg=
ulatory process [ https://substack.com/redirect/c379dad4-c9a9-4d80-96fc-b64=
fa1d7d8e3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ]. As Mark Nelson points out [ https://substack.com/redirect/51e4a616-05e=
6-4473-b014-2b5a3a0cd90b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Microsoft is paying a premium (~$100/MWh) over what the=
y=E2=80=99d have to pay for renewable energy because, =E2=80=9CNuclear almo=
st perfectly matches the specific service needs of the next generation of c=
entralized AI datacenters in a way distributed weather-based energy cannot =
do while keeping costs reasonable.=E2=80=9D
We are tapping the massive amounts of clean power trapped in atoms to creat=
e machine intelligences. Maybe, if we=E2=80=99re lucky, we=E2=80=99ll even =
be able to continue using washing machines instead of tedious labor to wash=
 our clothes [ https://substack.com/redirect/2d05fda2-ed28-45a0-ac6a-06031e=
40ad79?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
=2E=20
In short: welcome to the future we were promised.
(2) Brain goop that traps hunger neurons drives obesity [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/162e3770-0e25-4fc2-880d-538c6c9ce7e4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Max Kozlov for Nature
The buildup of sticky extracellular matrix ('goo') in the brain's appetite-=
control center blocks insulin from reaching hunger-regulating neurons, lead=
ing to metabolic disorders, but inhibiting this goo restores insulin sensit=
ivity and promotes weight loss=E2=80=94highlighting a new therapeutic targe=
t for treating diabetes and obesity.
Obesity has had a tough couple of years. First GLP-1s. Now this.
Researchers discovered that a buildup of a sticky extracellular matrix=E2=
=80=94or "goo"=E2=80=94in the brain's appetite-control center, specifically=
 the arcuate nucleus of the hypothalamus, prevents insulin from reaching ne=
urons that regulate hunger in mice. And, by inhibiting the production of th=
is goo, the researchers were able to restore insulin sensitivity and induce=
 weight loss.=20
Unlike GLP-1 therapies that mimic incretin hormones to enhance insulin secr=
etion and promote satiety, this new finding targets the sticky extracellula=
r matrix in the brain's appetite-control center to restore insulin signalin=
g directly to hunger-regulating neurons.=20
Even with the proliferation of GLP-1s, the world is still hungry for safe a=
nd effective solutions to obesity, and this =E2=80=9Cgoo=E2=80=9D seems to =
be another point of attack.
(3) The brain aged more slowly in monkeys given a cheap diabetes drug [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/ee2ffe2c-143e-454d-b254-e8894f56e769?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Max Kozlov for Nature
Monkeys that received metformin daily showed slower age-associated brain de=
cline [ https://substack.com/redirect/4ccef2a1-0ebb-437e-aeeb-9cd9f61a2b10?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] than d=
id those not given the drug. Furthermore, their neuronal activity resembled=
 that of monkeys about six years younger (equivalent to around 18 human yea=
rs) and the animals had enhanced cognition and preserved liver function.
Speaking of diabetes medications being repurposed, a study has shown that a=
 daily dose of metformin slowed biological aging in male monkeys, notably d=
elaying age-associated brain decline. Metformin is a low-cost, widely-used =
generic drug thta=E2=80=99s been on the market since the 1950s. Traditional=
ly it=E2=80=99s been used to treat diabetes by lowering blood sugar levels =
by improving the body's sensitivity to insulin.
In the study, monkeys given daily metformin exhibited neuronal activity res=
embling that of monkeys six years younger, enhanced cognition, and preserve=
d liver function. The drug appeared to slow aging in multiple tissues=E2=80=
=94including the lung, kidney, liver, skin, and brain's frontal lobe=E2=80=
=94and reduced chronic inflammation, a hallmark of aging.
If I=E2=80=99ve learned anything over the past couple of years it=E2=80=99s=
 that insulin regulation is a lot more important than we previously imagine=
d. Yes, it can treat things like diabetes and obesity, but it also seems to=
 play a surprisingly large role in brain health and aging processes.
In the U.S., a monthly supply of metformin can range from $4-$20 without in=
surance=E2=80=A6so less than a dollar per day. It=E2=80=99s super cheap and=
 widely available. Human trials to come (I hope).
(4) Aerospace=E2=80=99s Secret Search For Antigravity [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/eb8610a9-1ee4-40a0-ad9b-25483cb32e35?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Jesse Michels
Packy here. A few months ago, Jesse Michels recommended two books to me: Th=
e Man Who Mastered Gravity [ https://substack.com/redirect/bd157987-f015-4f=
6d-bb5f-860beac76769?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and The Hunt for Zero Point [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
5ad4ad29-25ec-48e8-898b-6a5198f70fa2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:  [ https://substack.com/redirect/5ad4ad29-2=
5ec-48e8-898b-6a5198f70fa2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]Inside the Classified World of Antigravity Technology [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/5ad4ad29-25ec-48e8-898b-6a5198f70fa2?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Both books c=
over the pursuit of antigravity technology decades ago, and both bent my br=
ain, but the latter is particularly notable because of its author: Nick Coo=
k [ https://substack.com/redirect/a23a79b0-892b-4a6b-96ef-4fe575219dbc?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
Cook did not come from the world of heretical physics or UFOs; he was the a=
viation editor for Jane=E2=80=99s Defence Weekly, a well-respected magazine=
 that provides high-quality journalism on military equipment, technology, a=
nd defense for defense industry professionals. When hints that the US gover=
nment might possess antigravity technology were first mysteriously dropped =
on his desk in the form of an old article, he tried to avoid the subject be=
cause it was well-known to tarnish the reputation of journalists who pursue=
d it.=20
But when Cook tried to get in touch with the Lockheed Martin VP mentioned i=
n the article, George Trimble, through a press contact at Lockheed, the con=
tact relayed back a message: =E2=80=9CHe doesn=E2=80=99t want to speak to m=
e. He doesn=E2=80=99t want to speak with you. Not now, not ever. I don=E2=
=80=99t mind telling you that he sounded scared.=E2=80=9D=20
That got Cook=E2=80=99s Spidey Senses tingling, and sent him down a years-l=
ong search for the truth about antigravity technology that took him across =
the world, from the US Defense Primes to the Nazi Foo Fighters and a small =
apartment in Canada where, serious observers suspected, a man controlled ob=
jects with his mind.
Cook himself doesn=E2=80=99t say whether he=E2=80=99s convinced the governm=
ent has antigravity technology in its possession. He=E2=80=99s a journalist=
, trying to report the facts. But if it does, it would be a technological b=
reakthrough that dwarves anything we=E2=80=99ve written about in the Weekly=
 Dose. Control of antigravity would mean spacecraft could sail through spac=
e (and even time) by harnessing electrogravitic effects as easily as a sail=
boat travels water propelled by wind.=20
The book is fascinating, and I recommend it, but if you just want to dip yo=
ur toes, Jesse sat down with Cook for an 80-minute video that I promise wil=
l at least get your mind racing a little bit. =20
There was a time, in the 1950s, when legitimate scientists and aerospace ex=
ecutives were convinced that antigravity was just around the corner. Then, =
all of a sudden, anyone who talked about the topic was labeled a quack. Odd=
 at the very least.=20
I like odd, particularly if it comes with even 0.01% odds of going interste=
llar. Seems like it=E2=80=99s at least worth a little more research. Watch =
the video. You be the judge.=20
(5) Daniel Yergin =E2=80=93 Oil Explains the Entire 20th Century [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/c7c1fd19-eb28-4a65-b8a8-f1d2319fb4ff?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Dwarkesh Patel
Daniel Yergin, author of The Prize: The Epic Quest for Oil, Money, and Powe=
r [ https://substack.com/redirect/57166821-edb5-465e-8eeb-f7cc83bfdeb9?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] went on Dw=
arkesh=E2=80=99 podcast this week. Published in 1991, The Prize follows the=
 rise of oil as a dominant economic force starting in the 1850s and up thro=
ugh to the =E2=80=9890s. The history of the 20th century is, in some ways, =
the history of oil.=20
In the 33 years since the book=E2=80=99s publication, some things have chan=
ged and some things haven=E2=80=99t. Energy is still, obviously, a shaping =
force and oil still has an outsized impact on global activities =E2=80=94 s=
ee: turmoil in the Middle East and the War in Ukraine =E2=80=94 but the ene=
rgy landscape is shifting. Yergin believes that oil and gas will still play=
 a prominent role in shaping geopolitics for decades to come, but that the =
renewable transition will shift nations=E2=80=99 priorities and relationshi=
ps.
Yergin predicts a shift from "big oil" to "big shovels," emphasizing the gr=
owing importance of mining and critical minerals for renewable technologies=
=2E This shift, he emphasizes, creates=20=
new geopolitical dynamics around the s=
upply chains and resources needed for clean energy. Yergin also predicts th=
at the shift towards renewables is a part of a larger trend away from globa=
lization. Countries are now more focused on energy security and resiliency =
and less singlemindedly focused on efficiency.
If the best way to predict the future is to study the past, and the past 15=
0+ years of global history is really just the history of oil, then a deep u=
nderstanding of the history of oil could be the most useful framework for p=
redicting and navigating the years to come. This podcast is a good place to=
 start if you want to understand that history, so give a listen. Plus, Dwar=
kesh is awesome.
Bonus: Black hole jets on the scale of the cosmic web [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/d326c298-880a-4f53-967c-880e77ef072f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Oei et al in Nature
When sustained for megayears, high-power jets from supermassive black holes=
 (SMBHs) become the largest galaxy-made structures in the Universe.
Throwing in a little bonus because this one=E2=80=99s just cool.=20
Researchers have discovered the largest-ever observed jets emitted by a sup=
ermassive black hole, named Porphyrion, extending across a staggering 23 mi=
llion light-years. A jet is a powerful stream of particles shooting out fro=
m near a black hole far into space. And the discovery of these jets implies=
 that such colossal jets may be more common than previously thought.=20
Porphyrion=E2=80=99s jets are so massive that they can eject material not j=
ust from their own galaxy but potentially into neighboring galaxies and int=
o the cosmic web of dark matter that structures the universe. The finding s=
uggests that massive blackholes not only impact their host galaxies but can=
 also impact the formation and growth of other galaxies.
Will the discovery of Porphyrion=E2=80=99s jets have any real impact on us =
today? No, not really. But it serves as a reminder of just how large and co=
mplex the system we live in is and how much there is to learn about it. It=
=E2=80=99s a reminder of =E2=80=9CThe Absurd=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 that phenom=
ena of feeling significant in our personal experiences while recognizing ou=
r minute existence within the immense cosmos.
Have a great weekend y=E2=80=99all.
